pr_body: Fixes #2212 Fixed lots of contrast problems and some clickable sizing problems. **Screenshots** ### Tab View 1. Missing label for tabs. 2. Close tab button is too small. ### Host book view t's complaining about duplicate labels or missing labels on the background of the cards. ### History/Bookmarks 1. The view all history switch is 48dp now. 2. It's complaining abut duplicate labels and image contrasts which is fine I think. (We can't do anything about the image contrast). ### Help activity This is also complaining about duplicate item descriptions and touch target sizes, both of which should be fine. ### Settings 1. Missing label on the zoom slider. It has a description that should be readable by a screen reader? ### Tab closed snackbar 1. The snackbar uses an odd color? It's a shade of white with black text and stands out a lot in dark mode. Any suggestions on if this should change? I made the button color darker to increase contrast.

<!--

- After solving the issue completely change it to "Fixes #{issue_number}.
-->
Fixes #2112 kind off

<!-- Add here what changes were made in this issue and if possible provide links. -->
The new UI is ready for a PR! It brings a bottom navigation bar and a drawer layout for some general menu items. Please install and test this branch as I am sure there are some newly introduced bugs from all these changes.

<!-- If possible, please add relevant screenshots / GIFs -->

So call it in onStart if it happens after `OnCreate` or just at the end of OnCreate. I truly hate this method as `postCreate` is not what happens immediately after `onCreate`

', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 14, 11, 47, 35, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'macgills', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 470576784, 'comment_body': "Oof, it's a lie", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 14, 11, 48, 31, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Frans-Lukas', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 470577095, 'comment_body': 'Hmm or I guess everything that happens after oncreate could be called onPostCreate', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 14, 11, 49, 18, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Frans-Lukas', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 470580162, 'comment_body': 'yeah but it violates the principle of Least Surprise. <!--
- Add the issue number here.

- If you haven't solved the issue completely use "Linked issue #{issue_number}.
- After solving the issue completely change it to "Fixes #{issue_number}.
-->
Fixes #2112 kind off

<!-- Add here what changes were made in this issue and if possible provide links. -->
The new UI is ready for a PR! It brings a bottom navigation bar and a drawer layout for some general menu items. Please install and test this branch as I am sure there are some newly introduced bugs from all these changes.

<!-- If possible, please add relevant screenshots / GIFs -->

**Screenshots** 
![Screenshot_1596795531](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/22193232/89636026-43186900-d8a8-11ea-8804-826f7a0d6333.png)
![Screenshot_1596795536](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/22193232/89636030-44499600-d8a8-11ea-9fec-6da02e5f4041.png)
![Screenshot_1596795541](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/22193232/89636031-44e22c80-d8a8-11ea-8f9b-de39fb21ee9d.png)
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 467822338, 'comment_body': "Shouldn't this be deleted? Or should it just be used instead of `NavigateTo`

I am not against some spring cleaning on this branch where you run the formatter over the codebase and delete any unused classes using the inspections", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 10, 10, 46, 4, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'macgills', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467824467, 'comment_body': "this doesn't need to be open or really exist at all, should just be OnlineLibraryFragment", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 10, 10, 50, 41, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'macgills', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467830003, 'comment_body': "you should invoke the other constructor with `this` so you don't repeat simple mappings that could introduce subtle bugs. Not very relevant in kotlin because it is an actually decent language", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 10, 11, 3, 39, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'macgills', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467859032, 'comment_body': 'removing marginTop and using `android:fitsSystemWindows="true"` would be better. 
Using margin may vary outputs on different devices. 
Here's an example :
![Webp net-resizeimage (5)](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/53831987/89781039-2d1cd980-db30-11ea-8714-f503cc1f5e00.png)
`android:fitsSystemWindows="true"` will work fine here.:smile:
', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 10, 12, 8, 22, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': '4shutosh', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467862390, 'comment_body': 'I suspected something would be odd with the margin. Thanks!', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 10, 12, 15, 39, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Frans-Lukas', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467870981, 'comment_body': "Opening a fragment needs to be followed by disabling the navigation drawer which you are correctly implementing using `handleDrawerOnNavigation()`. But what if that fragment is not opened from this activity the navDrawer won't be disbaled. 
For example if I bookmark a page from reader and open the bookmarks page using the snackbar action the navigation drawer won't be disabled.
This can be handeled using the `onOptionsItemSelected` on the fragment itself , if I'm not wrong the bookmarks fragment is using the `PageFragment` so making some changes there would fix this issue.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 10, 12, 32, 55, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': '4shutosh', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467881890, 'comment_body': 'Good catch! Will fix. ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 10, 12, 53, 36, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Frans-Lukas', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 470552541, 'comment_body': 'postCreate', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 14, 10, 47, 56, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'macgills', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 470553406, 'comment_body': 'postCreate, also this code looks like it fits in Core', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 14, 10, 50, 9, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'macgills', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 470573836, 'comment_body': "This would have to be called after the creation lifecycle step in Core? I'd agree with this answer https://stackoverflow.com/a/16564121 that it's ok to use in a parent activity. ", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 14, 11, 41, 21, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Frans-Lukas', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 470576404, 'comment_body': '![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/3358282/90246191-f1ce2380-de2b-11ea-91b3-881de05d6bee.png)

So call it in onStart if it happens after `OnCreate` or just at the end of OnCreate. I truly hate this method as `postCreate` is not what happens immediately after `onCreate`

', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 14, 11, 47, 35, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'macgills', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 470576784, 'comment_body': "Oof, it's a lie", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 14, 11, 48, 31, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Frans-Lukas', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 470577095, 'comment_body': 'Hmm or I guess everything that happens after oncreate could be called onPostCreate', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 14, 11, 49, 18, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Frans-Lukas', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 470580162, 'comment_body': 'yeah but it violates the principle of Least Surprise. I think the typical assumption is `this happens immediately after create` and you have to read the docs to discover it is a bastard.

Every android developer has to know the activity lifecycle, if only for it being asked in every interview, so lean on that shared knowledge', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 14, 11, 56, 49, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'macgills', 'type': 'User'}]

<!--
- Add the issue number here.

- If you haven't solved the issue completely use "Linked issue #{issue_number}.
- After solving the issue completely change it to "Fixes #{issue_number}.
-->
Fixes #2112 kind off

<!-- Add here what changes were made in this issue and if possible provide links. -->
The new UI is ready for a PR! It brings a bottom navigation bar and a drawer layout for some general menu items. Please install and test this branch as I am sure there are some newly introduced bugs from all these changes.

<!-- If possible, please add relevant screenshots / GIFs -->

**Screenshots** 
![Screenshot_1596795531](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/22193232/89636026-43186900-d8a8-11ea-8804-826f7a0d6333.png)
![Screenshot_1596795536](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/22193232/89636030-44499600-d8a8-11ea-9fec-6da02e5f4041.png)
![Screenshot_1596795541](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/22193232/89636031-44e22c80-d8a8-11ea-8f9b-de39fb21ee9d.png)
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 467822338, 'comment_body': "Shouldn't this be deleted? Or should it just be used instead of `NavigateTo`

I am not against some spring cleaning on this branch where you run the formatter over the codebase and delete any unused classes using the inspections", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 10, 10, 46, 4, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'macgills', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467824467, 'comment_body': "this doesn't need to be open or really exist at all, should just be OnlineLibraryFragment", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 10, 10, 50, 41, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'macgills', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467830003, 'comment_body': "you should invoke the other constructor with `this` so you don't repeat simple mappings that could introduce subtle bugs. Not very relevant in kotlin because it is an actually decent language", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 10, 11, 3, 39, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'macgills', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467859032, 'comment_body': 'removing marginTop and using `android:fitsSystemWindows="true"` would be better. 
Using margin may vary outputs on different devices. 
Here's an example :
![Webp net-resizeimage (5)](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/53831987/89781039-2d1cd980-db30-11ea-8714-f503cc1f5e00.png)
`android:fitsSystemWindows="true"` will work fine here.:smile:
', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 10, 12, 8, 22, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': '4shutosh', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467862390, 'comment_body': 'I suspected something would be odd with the margin. Thanks!', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 10, 12, 15, 39, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Frans-Lukas', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467870981, 'comment_body': "Opening a fragment needs to be followed by disabling the navigation drawer which you are correctly implementing using `handleDrawerOnNavigation()`. But what if that fragment is not opened from this activity the navDrawer won't be disbaled. 
For example if I bookmark a page from reader and open the bookmarks page using the snackbar action the navigation drawer won't be disabled.

pr_body: Fixes #2212 Fixed lots of contrast problems and some clickable sizing problems. **Screenshots** ### Tab View 1. Missing label for tabs. 2. Close tab button is too small. ### Host book view t's complaining about duplicate labels or missing labels on the background of the cards. ### History/Bookmarks 1. The view all history switch is 48dp now. 2. It's complaining abut duplicate labels and image contrasts which is fine I think. (We can't do anything about the image contrast). ### Help activity This is also complaining about duplicate item descriptions and touch target sizes, both of which should be fine. ### Settings 1. Missing label on the zoom slider. It has a description that should be readable by a screen reader? ### Tab closed snackbar 1. The snackbar uses an odd color? It's a shade of white with black text and stands out a lot in dark mode. Any suggestions on if this should change? I made the button color darker to increase contrast.

- After solving the issue completely change it to "Fixes #{issue_number}.

Fixes #2124 

<!-- Add here what changes were made in this issue and if possible provide links. -->
This PR rewrites the bookmarks activity to use better design patterns. This PR also contains the HistoryActivity rewrite as I used it for reference, this is only until I have finished the issue or until the HistoryActivity PR has been merged with the Dev branch. 

I haven't quite understood the repository compared to just using e.x. the HistoryDao/BookmarksDao. 
To delete bookmarks I tried:
```
repository.deleteBookmarks(bookmarkItems)
```
But that does not delete the items? Any advice/help is appreciated.

Have you much experience with generics? Essentially I want to see an abstract base class

```
<T:Page>PageActivity<T>
```

and implementations
```
HistoryActivity: PageActivity<HistoryItem>{ }
BookmarkActivity: PageActivity<BookmarkItem>{ }
```
and in the implementations they will only contain the parts that absolutely have to differ.

A similar methodology may be applied to ViewModel and State.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 17, 15, 20, 12, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'macgills', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 441633437, 'comment_body': 'ShowToast is a side effect, this should do nothing, you can just use the activityExtension `.toast()`', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 17, 15, 26, 1, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'macgills', 'type': 'User'}]

<!--
- Add the issue number here.

- If you haven't solved the issue completely use "Linked issue #{issue_number}.
- After solving the issue completely change it to "Fixes #{issue_number}.
-->
Fixes #2112 kind off

<!-- Add here what changes were made in this issue and if possible provide links. -->
The new UI is ready for a PR! It brings a bottom navigation bar and a drawer layout for some general menu items. Please install and test this branch as I am sure there are some newly introduced bugs from all these changes.

<!-- If possible, please add relevant screenshots / GIFs -->

**Screenshots** 
![Screenshot_1596795531](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/22193232/89636026-43186900-d8a8-11ea-8804-826f7a0d6333.png)
![Screenshot_1596795536](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/22193232/89636030-44499600-d8a8-11ea-9fec-6da02e5f4041.png)
![Screenshot_1596795541](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/22193232/89636031-44e22c80-d8a8-11ea-8f9b-de39fb21ee9d.png)

[{'comment_id': 467822338, 'comment_body': "Shouldn't this be deleted? Or should it just be used instead of `NavigateTo`

I am not against some spring cleaning on this branch where you run the formatter over the codebase and delete any unused classes using the inspections", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 10, 10, 46, 4, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'macgills', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467824467, 'comment_body': "this doesn't need to be open or really exist at all, should just be OnlineLibraryFragment", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 10, 10, 50, 41, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'macgills', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467830003, 'comment_body': "you should invoke the other constructor with `this` so you don't repeat simple mappings that could introduce subtle bugs. Not very relevant in kotlin because it is an actually decent language", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 10, 11, 3, 39, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'macgills', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467859032, 'comment_body': 'removing marginTop and using `android:fitsSystemWindows="true"` would be better. 
Using margin may vary outputs on different devices. 
Here's an example :
![Webp net-resizeimage (5)](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/53831987/89781039-2d1cd980-db30-11ea-8714-f503cc1f5e00.png)
`android:fitsSystemWindows="true"` will work fine here.:smile:
', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 10, 12, 8, 22, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': '4shutosh', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467862390, 'comment_body': 'I suspected something would be odd with the margin. Thanks!', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 10, 12, 15, 39, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Frans-Lukas', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467870981, 'comment_body': "Opening a fragment needs to be followed by disabling the navigation drawer which you are correctly implementing using `handleDrawerOnNavigation()`. But what if that fragment is not opened from this activity the navDrawer won't be disbaled. 
For example if I bookmark a page from reader and open the bookmarks page using the snackbar action the navigation drawer won't be disabled.
This can be handeled using the `onOptionsItemSelected` on the fragment itself , if I'm not wrong the bookmarks fragment is using the `PageFragment` so making some changes there would fix this issue.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 10, 12, 32, 55, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': '4shutosh', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467881890, 'comment_body': 'Good catch! Will fix. ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 10, 12, 53, 36, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Frans-Lukas', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 470552541, 'comment_body': 'postCreate', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 14, 10, 47, 56, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'macgills', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 470553406, 'comment_body': 'postCreate, also this code looks like it fits in Core', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 14, 10, 50, 9, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'macgills', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 470573836, 'comment_body': "This would have to be called after the creation lifecycle step in Core? I'd agree with this answer https://stackoverflow.com/a/16564121 that it's ok to use in a parent activity. ", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 14, 11, 41, 21, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Frans-Lukas', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 470576404, 'comment_body': '![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/3358282/90246191-f1ce2380-de2b-11ea-91b3-881de05d6bee.png)

So call it in onStart if it happens after `OnCreate` or just at the end of OnCreate. I truly hate this method as `postCreate` is not what happens immediately after `onCreate`

', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 14, 11, 47, 35, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'macgills', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 470576784, 'comment_body': "Oof, it's a lie", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 14, 11, 48, 31, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Frans-Lukas', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 470577095, 'comment_body': 'Hmm or I guess everything that happens after oncreate could be called onPostCreate', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 14, 11, 49, 18, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Frans-Lukas', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 470580162, 'comment_body': 'yeah but it violates the principle of Least Surprise. I think the typical assumption is `this happens immediately after create` and you have to read the docs to discover it is a bastard.

Every android developer has to know the activity lifecycle, if only for it being asked in every interview, so lean on that shared knowledge', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 14, 11, 56, 49, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'macgills', 'type': 'User'}]

<!--
- Add the issue number here.

- If you haven't solved the issue completely use "Linked issue #{issue_number}.
- After solving the issue completely change it to "Fixes #{issue_number}.
-->
Fixes #2124 

<!-- Add here what changes were made in this issue and if possible provide links. -->
This PR rewrites the bookmarks activity to use better design patterns. This PR also contains the HistoryActivity rewrite as I used it for reference, this is only until I have finished the issue or until the HistoryActivity PR has been merged with the Dev branch. 

I haven't quite understood the repository compared to just using e.x. the HistoryDao/BookmarksDao. 
To delete bookmarks I tried:
```
repository.deleteBookmarks(bookmarkItems)
```
But that does not delete the items? Any advice/help is appreciated.

Have you much experience with generics? Essentially I want to see an abstract base class

```
<T:Page>PageActivity<T>
```

and implementations
```
HistoryActivity: PageActivity<HistoryItem>{ }
BookmarkActivity: PageActivity<BookmarkItem>{ }
```
and in the implementations they will only contain the parts that absolutely have to differ.

A similar methodology may be applied to ViewModel and State.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 17, 15, 20, 12, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'macgills', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 441633437, 'comment_body': 'ShowToast is a side effect, this should do nothing, you can just use the activityExtension `.toast()`', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 17, 15, 26, 1, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'macgills', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_body: Fixes #2212 Fixed lots of contrast problems and some clickable sizing problems. **Screenshots** ### Tab View 1. Missing label for tabs. 2. Close tab button is too small. ### Host book view t's complaining about duplicate labels or missing labels on the background of the cards. ### History/Bookmarks 1. The view all history switch is 48dp now. 2. It's complaining abut duplicate labels and image contrasts which is fine I think. (We can't do anything about the image contrast). ### Help activity This is also complaining about duplicate item descriptions and touch target sizes, both of which should be fine. ### Settings 1. Missing label on the zoom slider. It has a description that should be readable by a screen reader? ### Tab closed snackbar 1. The snackbar uses an odd color? It's a shade of white with black text and stands out a lot in dark mode. Any suggestions on if this should change? I made the button color darker to increase contrast.
